.TH mtban 1 "2026-05-09" "1.0.0" "mtban"
.SH NAME
mtban \- manage MikroTik address-list entries via REST API
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mtban
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.B ban
.I IP
.br
.B mtban
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.B unban
.I IP
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B mtban
adds or removes an IP address from a MikroTik firewall address-list
using the RouterOS REST API (RouterOS 7+).
It can be used standalone or called by fail2ban as an action.
.SH ACTIONS
.TP
.B ban \fIIP\fR
Add \fIIP\fR to the address-list.
If the entry already exists, its comment (and optionally timeout) is updated.
.TP
.B unban \fIIP\fR
Remove \fIIP\fR from the address-list.
Does nothing if the entry does not exist.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-list " NAME"
Address-list name on the MikroTik device.
Default: \fBblocked\fR
.TP
.BI \-\-timeout " DURATION"
MikroTik timeout string (e.g. \fB1h\fR, \fB30m\fR, \fB1d\fR) or in seconds (e.g. \fB3600\fR).
When set, MikroTik will remove the entry automatically after expiry.
If omitted, the entry is permanent until explicitly unbanned.
.TP
.BI \-\-comment " TEXT"
Comment stored on the address-list entry.
Default: \fBmtban\fR
.TP
.BI \-\-config " FILE"
Path to the configuration file.
Default: \fB/etc/mtban/mtban.conf\fR
.SH CONFIGURATION
The configuration file is a simple key=value file:
.PP
.nf
url      = http://[mikrotik-ip]:[www-service-port]
username = mtban
password = your-api-secret
.fi
.PP
The file should be owned by root with mode
.BR 0600 .
It is created automatically from the example on first install.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
API call failed or configuration could not be read.
Errors are written to syslog (facility
.BR user ,
tag
.BR mtban ).
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/mtban/mtban.conf
Runtime configuration with credentials.
.TP
.B /etc/mtban/mtban.conf.example
Template copied to the above on first install.
.SH EXAMPLES
Ban an IP for one hour:
.PP
.nf
mtban ban 198.51.100.1 \-\-timeout 1h
.fi
.PP
Remove a ban:
.PP
.nf
mtban unban 198.51.100.1
.fi
.PP
Use a non-default config and list:
.PP
.nf
mtban ban 198.51.100.1 \-\-config /tmp/test.conf \-\-list quarantine
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR fail2ban\-client (1),
.BR fail2ban\-server (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Fabian Berg <fabian.berg@hb9hil.org>
